title: For Sale/Trade:  Genuine pre ban H&K 91 battle rifle
postcontent: Up for sale / trade is a genuine pre-ban 1981 Heckler & Koch 91 battle rifle. These are incredibly rare and hard to find. As a pre-ban it is one of a very limited number of  H&KS in the country which are eligible to be converted to full auto assuming you're willing to jump through the legal hoops and pay the cost to complete the conversion. What makes this rifle even more rare is that it comes with a factory installed ambi safety (almost unheard of) and also a shell deflector. These were never included in standard production, so the fact that they are factory  OEM parts makes this rifle a real one of a kind. This rifle had been professionally assessed by a well respected Knoxville gunsmith and is certified as all original parts and also in 90-95% condition. The rifle also has a collapsible stock rather than the fixed stock as well as fully operational sights peeps for zeroing at 100, 200, 300 and 400 yards. Book value on this rifle easily exceeds $3,000 and I have turned down a cash offer in that amount. This .308 is a true battle rifle and kicks like a mule - this is not a plinker or a good choice as al first rifle. Experienced shooters will appreciate this rifle, inexperienced shooters will regret the purchase / trade. If you have a serious interest in working a sale / trade on this rifle I would be happy for you to have it assessed by your own gunsmith prior to the transaction.

Glock magazines have very stiff springs when new and may be extremely difficult to load to full capacity. It may be necessary to use a Glock magazine loader (generally included in the Glock case with the handgun) to load the magazine to capacity or near capacity. 

If the last round appears impossible to load, for example if the magazine should hold 15 rounds and it will only accept 14, leave it loaded with 14 rounds for several days to allow the spring's tension to decrease. After a short time, the magazine should then accept its full capacity, but it may still be necessary to use the magazine loader. After several cycles of full capacity through empty, the magazine will be easier to load.

title: For Sale:  NEW ILLINOIS LAW DOES NOT REQUIRE USE OF FFL/DEALER
postcontent: The new law requiring sellers to check the validity of  the buyers FOID card does not require going through an FFL. You can check that the buyers card is current in one of two ways. First you may enter the buyers FOID card number into the Illinois State police website, thisay be done 24 hours a day. You may also call the illinois state police during regular daytime hours. Either way, if the card is valid they will give you a confirmation number that you include on the bill of sale. Also , there is no penalty for not doing the check. It is written in the law that " not doing so will not be charged with a crime or petty offense" .It does however release you from liability if for some  reason the buyers card is not valid and the gun is used in a crime. Gun shops would love it if we were forced to do transfers through them at $20 a crack, however that is simply not the case. Please don't go to them for accurate information as you probably won't get it.
